<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_LineToLine"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Linear maps transform lines to lines</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Meaning of condition 2) in the proposition</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Condition 2) above means that <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> transforms the linear motion <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{a} + t \Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> into the linear motion <math>
                  <latex>f(\Vect{a}) + tf(\Vect{v})</latex>
               </math>; i.e.</para.body>
         </para>
         <ul>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The place <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> through which the original motion passes at time <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> gets transformed into the place <math>
                        <latex>f(\Vect{a})</latex>
                     </math> through which the transformed motion passes at time <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The velocity vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math> of the original motion gets transformed into the velocity vector <math>
                        <latex>f(\Vect{v})</latex>
                     </math> of the transformed motion.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ul>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>A function <math>
               <latex>f\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
            </math> is linear if and only if it satisfies the following two conditions</para.body>
      </para>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>Whenever <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> are fixed, then <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{a} + t\cdot \Vect{v}) = f(\Vect{a}) + t\cdot f(\Vect{v})</latex>
                  </math> for all numbers <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
      </ol>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <caption>Suppose first that <math>
               <latex>f</latex>
            </math> is linear</caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> is has properties 1) and 2) above. Indeed, <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> enjoys 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>property 1)</hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearTrafo0To0"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up the proof of why this is so</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>. Moreover, <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> enjoys property 2) because
		</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{a} + t \Vect{v})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>f</latex>
                              </math> is linear, hence satisfies <math>
                                 <latex>f(\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) = f(\Vect{x}) + f(\Vect{y})</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{a}) + f(t \Vect{v})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>f</latex>
                              </math>is linear, hence satisfies <math>
                                 <latex>f(t \Vect{x}) = t f(\Vect{x})</latex>
                              </math>
                           </para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{a}) + t\cdot f(\Vect{v})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>as required.</para.body>
         </para>
         <caption>Suppose <math>
               <latex>f</latex>
            </math> satisfies properties 1) and 2) above</caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> is linear. Now if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> are arbitrary in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>, they determine the linear motion <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{a}(t) = \Vect{x} + t \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>  in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>. Therefore, setting <math>
                  <latex>t:=1</latex>
               </math>, we obtain</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{x} + \Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{x} + 1\cdot \Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{x}) + 1\cdot f(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{x}) + f(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>So <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> commutes with vector addition. To see that <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> commutes with scalar multiplication, let  <math>
                  <latex>t\in\RNr</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math> be arbitrary. Then</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(t\cdot \Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{0} + t\cdot \Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Because of assmumption 2. in the proposition: with <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{a}:=\Vect{0}</latex>
                              </math> and <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{v}:=\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>f(\Vect{0}) + t\cdot f(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Remember: we assume that <math>
                                 <latex>f(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                              </math>
                           </para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot f(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>So <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> is linear. â€“ The proof is complete.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
